<Document>
<name>Monument Valley — US-163</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Monument Valley — US-163</h2><p><i>Utah / Arizona, USA · US-163, Bluff UT to Kayenta AZ</i></p><p><b>The Hollywood image of the American West — the John Ford backdrop you've seen a hundred times.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>106 km (66 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Spring and fall (summer brings extreme heat, winter brings snow on north end)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>High winds and blowing sand; livestock on road; respect Navajo Nation closures and tribal fees</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>121</td></tr></table><hr><p>This 110 km stretch is what most people see when they close their eyes and think 'American West.' Every John Ford western (Stagecoach, The Searchers, Fort Apache); the closing run of Forrest Gump; Mission: Impossible 2; the Roadrunner cartoons. The mesas and buttes are 50-million-year-old De Chelly sandstone left behind as softer rock eroded around them — geology's last men standing. The land is the Navajo Nation; the loop drive into the valley itself requires a tribal-park fee. Stop at John Ford's Point. Stay overnight if you can — sunset and sunrise are not optional here.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Mexican Hat rock</b> — Balanced sandstone disk on a thin pedestal — the geological inspiration for the town's name.</li><li><b>Forrest Gump Point</b> — Mile marker 13 on US-163. The exact pavement where Tom Hanks stops running. Stand in the road for the photo (carefully).</li><li><b>The Mittens viewpoint</b> — Two mesas with a thumb-like spire each — perhaps the most photographed natural feature in the western US. Look-out is at the Navajo Tribal Park visitor center.</li><li><b>Goulding's Trading Post</b> — Where John Ford filmed Stagecoach in 1939, putting the valley on cinematic maps. Original lodge open as a museum.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
